{"type": "root", "attrs": {"icon": "SHELF/cool_within_object", "tags": "viscousfluids"}, "body": [{"level": 0, "type": "title", "indent": 0, "text": ["Cool Within Object"], "extent": [54, 77]}, {"type": "summary", "indent": 0, "text": ["Turns an object into a source of cooling when particles pass through."], "extent": [77, 155]}, {"level": 2, "id": null, "container": true, "type": "h", "indent": 0, "text": ["Overview"], "extent": [155, 170], "body": [{"type": "para", "indent": 0, "text": ["This tool will take an object and turn it into a source of cooling when particles pass through. You would typically use this tool if you want to cool a fluid in your scene that has been set up with another one of the tools on the Viscous Fluid shelf. For example, if you are simulating a river of lava, you can create cool zones causing the fluid to harden when it reaches certain areas to control the flow of the river."], "extent": [170, 593]}]}, {"level": 2, "id": null, "container": true, "type": "h", "indent": 0, "text": ["Using Cool Within Object"], "extent": [593, 624], "body": [{"type": "ord_group", "body": [{"blevel": 2, "type": "ord", "indent": 0, "text": ["Select the object to be the cooling source."], "extent": [624, 672]}, {"blevel": 2, "type": "ord", "indent": 0, "text": ["Click the ", {"scheme": "Icon", "value": "SHELF/cool_within_object", "type": "link", "text": "", "fullpath": "/shelf/SHELF/cool_within_object"}, {"type": "ui", "text": ["Cool Within Object"]}, " tool on the Viscous Fluids tab. "], "extent": [672, 772]}, {"blevel": 2, "type": "ord", "indent": 0, "text": ["Select the hot fluid to be cooled, and press ", {"keys": ["Enter"], "type": "keys", "text": null}, "."], "extent": [772, 831], "body": [{"type": "para", "indent": 4, "text": ["For specific parameter information, see the ", {"scheme": "Node", "value": "/nodes/dop/flipobject", "type": "link", "text": ["FLIP Object"], "fullpath": "/nodes/dop/flipobject"}, " and ", {"scheme": "Node", "value": "/nodes/dop/popattribfromvolume", "type": "link", "text": ["POP Attribute from Volume"], "fullpath": "/nodes/dop/popattribfromvolume"}, " help pages."], "extent": [831, 991]}], "container": true}], "container": true}, {"type": "para", "indent": 0, "text": [{"scheme": "Image", "value": "/images/shelf/coolwithinobject.jpg", "type": "img", "text": ""}], "extent": [991, 1036]}, {"level": 3, "id": "heatvscool", "container": true, "type": "h", "indent": 0, "text": ["Heat Within Object vs Cool Within Object"], "extent": [1690, 1749], "body": [{"type": "para", "indent": 4, "text": ["The ", {"scheme": null, "value": "/shelf/heatwithinobject", "type": "link", "text": ["Heat Within Object"], "fullpath": "/shelf/heatwithinobject"}, " and ", {"scheme": null, "value": "/shelf/coolwithinobject", "type": "link", "text": ["Cool Within Object"], "fullpath": "/shelf/coolwithinobject"}, " tools are very similar. The main difference is that the heating tool has a high ", {"type": "ui", "text": ["Increase Rate"]}, " meaning that melting objects will heat up, and the cooling tool has a high ", {"type": "ui", "text": ["Decrease Rate"]}, " meaning that objects will cool off quickly."], "extent": [1749, 2092]}, {"type": "para", "indent": 4, "text": ["The ", {"type": "ui", "text": ["Increase/Decrease Rate"]}, " parameters can be found on the ", {"scheme": "Node", "value": "/nodes/dop/popattribfromvolume", "type": "link", "text": ["POP Attribute from Volume"], "fullpath": "/nodes/dop/popattribfromvolume"}, " node, and work similar to the way the ", {"type": "ui", "text": ["Temperature Diffusion"]}, " parameters on the ", {"scheme": "Node", "value": "/nodes/dop/gastemperatureupdate", "type": "link", "text": ["Gas Temperature Update"], "fullpath": "/nodes/dop/gastemperatureupdate"}, " node work. They control how quickly the temperature from your heated or cooled object will affect your viscous fluid. "], "extent": [2092, 2473]}]}]}], "title": ["Cool Within Object"], "summary": ["Turns an object into a source of cooling when particles pass through."], "included": ["/fluid/lava"]}